## Core Rules

1. **Read before acting.** Always read the relevant files before doing work.
2. **Save progress constantly.** Update files after completing any task. Never rely on conversation memory.
3. **Ask before assuming.** If unclear, ask. Don't guess.
4. **Be concise.** Skip preambles. Max 3 sentences for simple answers.
5. **Do what's asked. Nothing more.** Mention related ideas, but ask before acting on them.
6. **One thing at a time.** Process items sequentially. Read, fully process, complete, then next.

---

## Domain Isolation

**When working on a domain, read ONLY that domain's files. Never explore "just in case."**

| If working on... | Read ONLY these files |
|------------------|----------------------|
| [domain-1-name] | [DOMAIN1]_QUEUE.md, [DOMAIN1].md |
| [domain-2-name] | [DOMAIN2]_QUEUE.md, [DOMAIN2].md |
| [domain-3-name] | [DOMAIN3]_QUEUE.md, [DOMAIN3].md |

Cross-domain work: If the task spans multiple domains, read both. Not before.
If unsure which domain: ASK. Don't explore multiple domains to figure it out.

---

## File Structure

Every domain has up to 4 files:
- `{DOMAIN}_QUEUE.md` - Active work (read FIRST every session)
- `{DOMAIN}.md` - Reference/knowledge base (read when needed)
- `{DOMAIN}_LOG.md` - History (rarely read unless looking back)
- `{DOMAIN}_HANDOFF.md` - Session relay baton (read at session start)

**QUEUE file first. Always.** It tells you what's active.
**Reference doc only when needed.** If the QUEUE gives enough context, skip it.
**Never read LOG files** unless asked for historical context.

---

## Session Rules

**Start of session:**
1. Read the QUEUE file. Always.
2. Read the HANDOFF file to see what happened last session.
3. Report what's active and what's next.

**During session:**
- Update QUEUE after completing any task (don't wait until wrap-up)
- One task at a time - finish and check off before starting the next
- Write decisions, corrections, and findings to files immediately

**End of session ("wrap up"):**
1. Update QUEUE - check off completed items, add new tasks, update Quick Resume
2. Write HANDOFF - what was done, in progress, blocked, context for next session
3. Git commit if the repo is set up: `git add {files} && git commit -m '{domain}: session wrap-up'`

---

## Agent Delegation

Delegate to sub-agents to keep main context clean. Every agent gets its own context window.

- 3+ file reads -> prefer an agent
- Quick lookups -> fast/cheap model (e.g., Haiku)
- Research and analysis -> balanced model (e.g., Sonnet)
- Complex reasoning -> full model (e.g., Opus), use sparingly
- Always summarise agent results concisely. Don't parrot everything back.

